article.description: The Dallas Mavericks' Big Three strutted against a fading team that hasn't won in a month.
article.headline: Nowitzki's 35 help send Raptors to 13th defeat in a row

images.name: Nowitzki, Dirk  020307 inline
images.caption: A 35-point effort by Dirk Nowitzki was worth a pat on the head from Steve Nash.

article.linkText: Mavericks have no trouble adding to Raptors' woes
article.story:
DALLAS (AP) -- The Dallas Mavericks' Big Three strutted against a fading team that hasn't won in a month. Dirk Nowitzki buried long shots and dunks to score 35 points, Michael Finley soared over and around Vince Carter for 25 and Steve Nash combined 19 points with a season-best 15 assists, carrying Dallas past the hapless Toronto Raptors 122-103 Thursday night. The bonus prize for the Mavericks was becoming the first team in the NBA with 43 victories. For Toronto, the defeat was their 13th in a row, prompting a closed-door meeting following the game. "We're on the verge of something good," Finley said. "Right now, we can't look at the standings and hope other teams lose. If we keep winning, I like our position." At 43-18, Dallas is in a virtual tie with Sacramento for the best record in the NBA. The Kings (42-17) have a slightly better winning percentage, .712 to .705. The Los Angeles Lakers are fighting for the top seed in the West, too, at 42-18 (.700). "We like stuff like that," said Nowitzki, who scored at least 30 points for the 19th time. "We want to finish as high as we can. If we have a chance to be the best in the league at the end of the season, we're going to go for it." Coach Don Nelson rewarded the team with a day off Friday, their first since acquiring four players from Denver on Feb. 21. The Raptors are within two games of the longest losing streak by any team this season. Two after that and they'll tie the worst skid in franchise history. "It's a new experience -- I've never been in that position before," said Toronto's Lenny Wilkens, the winningest coach in NBA history. "I'm sure they want to win so bad. They know that there's two or three games that got away from us and had they not, the streak doesn't exist." Finley, Nowitzki and Nash were especially dominant in the third quarter, scoring 29 of the Mavs' 33 points. Nash and Nowitzki had 10 each and Finley added nine. The biggest surprise for the Mavericks was their accuracy, a season-best 65 percent, one game after hitting only 37 percent and scoring a season-low 81 points. Dallas made 12 of 15 shots (80 percent) in the fourth quarter. The rims seemed so wide that Shawn Bradley went 3-for-3, including two long jumpers. Dallas did it primarily by taking easy shots. The game was heavy on layups and dunks, rather than the mad-bomber style the perimeter-oriented team often relies on. The Mavericks' offensive success enabled them to win easily despite being outrebounded 51-34. "We made a lot of jumpers, but we also had a lot of layups and open looks," Nash said. Toronto trailed by 11 in the first quarter, then led briefly in the middle quarters -- yet never by more than one. The Raptors scored only 23 points in the third quarter to fall behind by double digits and never made it close again. Carter led Toronto with 19 points, but most came after the game was decided. One game after tying his season high with 43 points, he was shut out the first 10 minutes and had only one field goal in the first half. Keon Clark had 18 points, including an incredible throw-down over 7-foot-6 Bradley. Clark and Antonio Davis each had 15 rebounds. Morris Peterson scored 16. Toronto, which beat Dallas by 14 in the first meeting this season, marked the one-month anniversary of its last victory by matching its longest losing streak since 1998. The Raptors are four defeats from tying the worst skid in franchise history. Their next two games are against Miami and Orlando, then they get New Jersey, Sacramento and Minnesota, three of the top five teams in the league. Game notes
With six assists, Carter reached 1,000 for his career. ... Toronto had been 12-1 when scoring 100 points. ... Both teams hit 3-pointers, extending their streak of doing so to 264 games. They are tied for the longest stretch in the NBA. ... The game featured two of the three winningest coaches in NBA history. Wilkens is No. 1 and Dallas' Don Nelson is No. 3. ... The Mavericks needed only six baskets to get all five starters in the scoring column. ... Toronto, meanwhile, got its first 17 points from only two players, Clark and Jerome Williams. Davis joined them with 1:52 left in the first quarter. ... Hakeem Olajuwon passed Oscar Robertson for ninth on the career list for minutes played.
